Perimeter Defense - Email Security > [T4]: Early Phishing Detection Using Honeypots Tokens

 

A honeypot is a hacker's trap. SOC analysts deploy different types of honeypots to get notified about the attacker's attempts and movements, hopefully without the attacker being aware.

 

A typical phishing campaign involves cloning one of the target organization's login pages and hosting it on an attacker-controlled server. What if we can detect a phishing attack in its early stages when the attacker clones the login page -before sending the phishing email? That would be very effective from a response perspective.

 

SOC analysts can write a simple Javascript file that acts as a honeypot and place it in the HTML code of the login page. Every time the login page is visited, the JS checks the domain hosting the web page and triggers an alert if that domain is not the legitimate domain.

 

For example, suppose attackers are running after cyberdefenders.org users' credentials. In that case, they will clone one of cyberdefenders.org login pages such as https://cyberdefenders.org/login and host the cloned copy on another look-alike domain such as https://cyberdefnders.org/login (note the missing 'e'). Each time the fake login page is visited, the JS will trigger an alert because the page is accessed via cyberdefnders.org (the fake domain) and not the legit cyberdefenders.org 

 

The JS does this using the document.domain property as in the following code snippet:

if (document.domain != "cyberdefenders.org") {$action}
 

The cool guys @ThinkstCanary built a free tool to create this honeypot JS for anyone. To use it, visit https://canarytokens.org/generate and create a new token of type cloned website. It will ask for a few details and generate a JS honeypot that you can include on your login page. Every time the login page is accessed through the non-legit domain, it will send an email alert to an address of your choice. It can also send Slack notifications via webhooks.

Figure - zoom in

 

We can also use a JS obfuscator to make it harder for attackers to discover the functionality of the honeypot JS. Javascript Obfuscator converts the JavaScript source code into obfuscated and hard-to-read form. Attackers can easily deobfuscate the script and see the original code. It just makes it harder for attackers to discover the honeypot JS.
